## **2. Implementing Responsive Width for `.overlay-widget`**

To set the width of `.overlay-widget` to **90%** on mobile devices, follow these steps:

### **a. Modify the Mobile Media Query**

Locate the existing media query for smaller screens in your `style.css`. It should look something like this:

```css
/* Media Queries for Smaller Screens (Mobile) */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .overlay-widget {
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .overlay-widget h1 {
    font-size: 1.4em; /* Smaller heading on mobile */
  }

  .overlay-widget p {
    font-size: 1em; /* Smaller paragraph text on mobile */
  }

  .custom-link {
    font-size: 15px;
    padding: 10px 15px;
  }
}
```

### **b. Add Width Property**

Within this media query, add the `width` property to `.overlay-widget` to set it to **90%** of its parent container's width (which is `.landing-section` set to 100% width).

Here's the updated media query:

```css
/* Media Queries for Smaller Screens (Mobile) */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .overlay-widget {
    width: 90%; /* Sets the width to 90% of the parent */
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .overlay-widget h1 {
    font-size: 1.4em; /* Smaller heading on mobile */
  }

  .overlay-widget p {
    font-size: 1em; /* Smaller paragraph text on mobile */
  }

  .custom-link {
    font-size: 15px;
    padding: 10px 15px;
  }
}
```

### **c. (Optional) Add Maximum Width for Better Control**

While setting the width to 90% ensures responsiveness, you might also want to set a `max-width` to prevent the overlay from becoming excessively wide on larger screens within the mobile media query. However, since the media query targets screens **up to 768px**, this is generally not necessary. If desired, here's how you can add it:

```css
.overlay-widget {
  width: 90%;
  max-width: 400px; /* Adjust as needed */
  padding: 20px;
}
```

