## **1. Refactor to Use CSS for Background Images**

To effectively manage background images through CSS, it's advisable to define them within your `style.css` rather than setting them inline in your `index.php`. This allows media queries to target and override background images based on screen size.

### **a. Remove Inline Background Image from `index.php`**

Locate the inline `background-image` in your `index.php` file and remove it. This ensures that CSS manages all background images.

**Original `index.php`:**

```php
<section class="landing-section" style="background-image: url('<?php echo esc_url( get_template_directory_uri() . '/images/p.png' ); ?>');">
    <div class="overlay-widget">
        <!-- Content -->
    </div>
</section>
```

**Updated `index.php`:**

```php
<section class="landing-section">
    <div class="overlay-widget">
        <!-- Content -->
    </div>
</section>
```

### **b. Define Background Images in CSS**

Move the background image definitions to your `style.css` file. This allows you to leverage media queries effectively.

**Updated `.landing-section` Styles in `style.css`:**

```css
/* Landing Section Styling */
.landing-section {
    position: relative; /* Establishes a positioning context for the overlay */
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9; /* Maintains a 16:9 aspect ratio */
    background-size: cover; /* Ensures the image covers the entire section */
    background-position: center; /* Centers the background image */
    background-repeat: no-repeat; /* Prevents background image repetition */
    background-image: url('images/p-mobile.png'); /* Default mobile background image */
}
```

**Note:** Since CSS files are static, embedding PHP within `style.css` isn't straightforward. Instead, consider defining the background image in CSS without PHP or use inline styles sparingly for dynamic content. For dynamic images, an alternative approach involving CSS variables or inline styles may be necessary.

However, for simplicity and effectiveness, it's recommended to manage background images directly in CSS, using media queries to switch images based on screen size.

