## **2. Utilize CSS Media Queries to Change Background Images**

CSS media queries allow you to apply different styles based on specific conditions, such as screen width. You can define multiple background images for different viewport sizes, ensuring that the most appropriate image is loaded for each device.

### **a. Define Default Background Image**

Ensure that the `.landing-section` has a default background image suitable for mobile devices or the smallest screen size.

```css
.landing-section {
    /* ... existing styles ... */
    background-image: url('images/p-mobile.png'); /* Mobile default background image */
}
```

### **b. Override Background Image for Larger Screens**

Use media queries to specify different background images for larger screens.

```css
/* Tablets */
@media (min-width: 600px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: url('images/p-tablet.png'); /* Tablet background image */
    }
}

/* Small Desktops */
@media (min-width: 992px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: url('images/p-small-desktop.png'); /* Small desktop background image */
    }
}

/* Large Desktops */
@media (min-width: 1200px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: url('images/p-desktop.png'); /* Large desktop background image */
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

- **Default (`background-image: p-mobile.png`):** Applied to all devices by default, typically mobile devices.

- **`@media (min-width: 600px)`:** When the viewport width is **600px** or larger (common tablet size), the background image changes to `p-tablet.png`.

- **`@media (min-width: 992px)`:** When the viewport width is **992px** or larger (common small desktop size), the background image changes to `p-small-desktop.png`.

- **`@media (min-width: 1200px)`:** When the viewport width is **1200px** or larger (common large desktop size), the background image changes to `p-desktop.png`.

**Note:** Adjust the `min-width` values and image paths based on your design requirements and the actual screen sizes you target.

### **c. Complete Example of Background Image Media Queries**

Here’s a more comprehensive example, considering various device widths:

```css
/* Landing Section Styling */
.landing-section {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
    background-size: cover;
    background-position: center;
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    background-image: url('images/p-mobile.png'); /* Mobile default background image */
}

/* Tablets */
@media (min-width: 600px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: url('images/p-tablet.png'); /* Tablet background image */
    }
}

/* Small Desktops */
@media (min-width: 992px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: url('images/p-small-desktop.png'); /* Small desktop background image */
    }
}

/* Large Desktops */
@media (min-width: 1200px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: url('images/p-desktop.png'); /* Large desktop background image */
    }
}
```

**Image Selection Tips:**

- **Optimize Images:** Ensure each background image is optimized for web use to reduce load times. Use tools like [TinyPNG](https://tinypng.com/) or [ImageOptim](https://imageoptim.com/) to compress images without losing quality.

- **Use Appropriate Sizes:** Select images that match the dimensions required for each screen size to avoid unnecessary data usage and ensure visual clarity.

- **Consider Modern Formats:** Utilize modern image formats like **WebP** for better compression rates. Provide fallback images in **JPEG** or **PNG** for browsers that do not support WebP.

