## **3. Advanced: Using CSS Variables for Background Images**

If you require more dynamic control over background images, you can use **CSS variables** in conjunction with media queries to manage different background images efficiently.

### **a. Define CSS Variables**

Set up CSS variables for background images and update them within media queries.

```css
:root {
    /* Default (Mobile) Background Image */
    --landing-bg-image: url('images/p-mobile.png');
}

/* Tablets */
@media (min-width: 600px) {
    :root {
        --landing-bg-image: url('images/p-tablet.png');
    }
}

/* Small Desktops */
@media (min-width: 992px) {
    :root {
        --landing-bg-image: url('images/p-small-desktop.png');
    }
}

/* Large Desktops */
@media (min-width: 1200px) {
    :root {
        --landing-bg-image: url('images/p-desktop.png');
    }
}
```

### **b. Apply the CSS Variable to `.landing-section`**

Use the CSS variable for the `background-image` property.

```css
.landing-section {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
    background-size: cover;
    background-position: center;
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    background-image: var(--landing-bg-image);
}
```

**Benefits:**

- **Centralized Control:** Manage background images from one place using CSS variables.

- **Enhanced Readability:** Makes the CSS more maintainable by clearly defining image sources.

- **Ease of Updates:** Changing the image for a specific screen size only requires updating the URL in the variable definition within the corresponding media query.

**Note:** Ensure that the images exist at the specified paths and that they are optimized for their respective screen sizes.

