## **5. Alternative Approach: Using the `<picture>` Element**

While CSS media queries are effective for background images, sometimes it's beneficial to use the `<picture>` element for more control over responsive images, especially if the image is content rather than decorative.

However, the `<picture>` element is typically used with `<img>` tags, not for CSS background images. So, this approach would require restructuring your HTML and CSS.

**Example:**

```html
<section class="landing-section">
    <picture>
        <source media="(min-width: 1200px)" srcset="images/p-desktop.webp" type="image/webp">
        <source media="(min-width: 1200px)" srcset="images/p-desktop.png" type="image/png">
        <source media="(min-width: 992px)" srcset="images/p-small-desktop.webp" type="image/webp">
        <source media="(min-width: 992px)" srcset="images/p-small-desktop.png" type="image/png">
        <source media="(min-width: 600px)" srcset="images/p-tablet.webp" type="image/webp">
        <source media="(min-width: 600px)" srcset="images/p-tablet.png" type="image/png">
        <img src="images/p-mobile.png" alt="Landing Background"> <!-- Default image -->
    </picture>
    <div class="overlay-widget">
        <!-- Content -->
    </div>
</section>
```

**Notes:**

- This method allows different images to be loaded based on screen width, optimizing performance.

- However, it changes the background image approach to using actual `<img>` elements, which may affect layout and accessibility.

- Use this approach only if the background images are meaningful content.

