## **8. Alternative Approach: CSS Variables for Background Images**

If you require a more dynamic and maintainable approach, especially if background images need to change based on various conditions beyond screen width, consider using **CSS variables**.

### **a. Define CSS Variables for Background Images**

```css
:root {
    --landing-bg-mobile: url('images/p-mobile.png');
    --landing-bg-tablet: url('images/p-tablet.png');
    --landing-bg-small-desktop: url('images/p-small-desktop.png');
    --landing-bg-desktop: url('images/p-desktop.png');
}

/* Set default background image using a CSS variable */
.landing-section {
    background-image: var(--landing-bg-mobile);
}

/* Tablets */
@media (min-width: 600px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: var(--landing-bg-tablet);
    }
}

/* Small Desktops */
@media (min-width: 992px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: var(--landing-bg-small-desktop);
    }
}

/* Large Desktops */
@media (min-width: 1200px) {
    .landing-section {
        background-image: var(--landing-bg-desktop);
    }
}
```

**Benefits:**

- **Centralized Image Management:** All background images are defined in the `:root` selector, making it easier to update paths or switch images.

- **Enhanced Readability:** Clearly named variables indicate the purpose and target device for each image.

- **Ease of Updates:** Updating a background image only requires changing the URL in the variable definition within the corresponding media query.

**Note:** Ensure that the images exist at the specified paths and that they are optimized for their respective screen sizes.

